# App shell directory boundary (`components/dashboard/`)

Mirrors **AGENTS.md §7 → Design system** (app shell row) and **[`docs/design-system/app-shell-learnings.md`](../../docs/design-system/app-shell-learnings.md)**. If this rule and `AGENTS.md` diverge, follow `AGENTS.md` and fix this rule in the same PR.

## Authority

- **`components/dashboard/`** owns **ERP dashboard chrome only**: shell composition, module navigation chrome, loading affordances shared across `/o/[orgSlug]/dashboard/**`. No tenant business rules, no DB access, no Server Actions.
- **IAM auth surfaces** (sign-in, interruption flows) use **`components/auth/`** and **`#lib/auth`** — do not fold IAM workflows into dashboard shell components.
- **Shell component registry (current):** `dashboard-shell.tsx` (composition root), `app-sidebar.tsx` (left rail, `collapsible="icon"`, cookie `sidebar_width`), `app-topbar.tsx` (L1 + L2 two-layer header), `nav-data.ts` (registry-aligned nav items, client-safe), `breadcrumbs.tsx` (L2 breadcrumb row), `module-subnav.tsx` (L2 module tab slot), `right-inspector.tsx` + `inspector-context.tsx` (right inspector, `side="right"`, cookies `inspector_state` + `inspector_width`), `org-switcher.tsx` (L1 org-switching pill), `use-resizable-width.ts` (pointer drag hook, cookie persistence, a11y arrow-key resize), `resize-handle.tsx` (visual drag handle presenter), `command-palette.tsx` + `command-palette-context.tsx` + `command-palette-trigger.tsx` (Cmd/Ctrl+K palette — navigation-only, three groups: modules / orgs / admin).

## Shell ownership doctrine

The app shell is **operational routing infrastructure**, not marketing UI or module feature UI.

Prioritize, in order:

1. Navigation continuity and orientation  
2. Organization context clarity (slug-bound URLs per locale-first contract)  
3. Capability discoverability (what the user can do in this org)  
4. Layout stability (no padding ↔ sidebar width drift)  
5. Keyboard and accessibility consistency  

**Before** visual differentiation, motion novelty, or “workspace intelligence” UX.

## Rules

- **Registry-aligned navigation.** Prefer a single nav registry next to [`lib/dashboard-module-paths.ts`](../../lib/dashboard-module-paths.ts), aligned with the **registry discipline** used by org admin (`ORG_ADMIN_CAPABILITIES`). Avoid orphaned hard-coded `NAV_ITEMS` arrays that drift from path helpers.
- **Layout coupling.** Prefer **shadcn `SidebarProvider` + `SidebarInset`** and CSS variables (`--sidebar-width`, `--sidebar-width-icon`) over hand-duplicated `padding-left` / `margin` that mirror sidebar width — that pattern diverges on resize, collapsible state, and hydration.
- **Secondary rails (e.g. right inspector).** Do not nest another full `Sidebar` beside `main` inside `SidebarInset` — use an in-flow `aside` with explicit width (`0` when closed). See `.cursor/rules/frontend-quality-contract.mdc` §11 → *Secondary rails inside `SidebarInset`*.
- **Shell boundaries.** Prefer **route groups** and layout nesting for “shell vs no-shell” — avoid pathname-regex wrappers at the locale root (fragile and hard to reason about as routes evolve).
- **Decomposition.** Split shell files **only when ownership stabilizes**. Minimum viable decomposition is **`app-sidebar` + `nav-data`** (names illustrative — fit existing file naming). Do **not** cargo-cult OSS template granularity (`nav-group.tsx`, `nav-user.tsx`, `team-switcher.tsx`, …) unless each file has a distinct, sustained ownership boundary in this repo.
- **Scoped enhancements.** Org switcher, command palette, breadcrumbs, and similar affordances are **separate deliverables** — do not bundle into a monolithic “shell rewrite”. Command palette must not turn into open-ended “workspace intelligence.”
- **Boring shell.** No animated chrome for novelty; density and calm ERP posture beat dashboard marketing energy.

## Forbidden

- Tenant-scoped **ERP/domain logic** inside `components/dashboard/**`.
- **Deep imports** into `lib/features/<module>/data/...` from dashboard shell — consume **`#features/<module>`** barrels only where a shell truly needs a typed contract, and keep imports minimal.
- **Cross-tenant or slug-from-client** assumptions — org slug and navigation targets come from server guards + existing path builders; shell components remain dumb presenters of props passed from RSC parents where possible.
